6 hoc tempore z'jhso .· the occurrences above alluded to were of compara· tively old date ; while the scarcity of corn was great at Rome in 58 B.C. and the years following, and led to the appointment of Pompeius as praefectus annonae for five years with extraordinary powers. He had authority to command all towns in the empire to send comto Rome at a fixed price (Att. 4, 1, 7), and may have compelled the Gaditanes to send it. From Cic.'s words, however (ut saepe ante), it seems that the corn sent from Gades was a gift. Subject states anxious to cultivate the favour of the Romans often made such gifts in time of scarcity (so Hiero in 215 B.c.; see Liv. 22, 37, 6).
